00:10:48,390 --> 00:10:49,010
Cool.

276
00:10:49,470 --> 00:10:51,230
Let's go at seven.

277
00:10:52,330 --> 00:10:53,410
Sounds good.

278
00:10:54,010 --> 00:10:55,590
Let's invite Jens, too.

279
00:10:56,570 --> 00:10:57,110
Okay.

280
00:10:57,470 --> 00:10:59,490
So you notice that we didn't wait for

281
00:10:59,490 --> 00:11:02,050
me to hit done before showing Stephanie the

282
00:11:02,050 --> 00:11:04,270
message, but rather, and this was difficult to

283
00:11:04,270 --> 00:11:07,150
do, we transmit live almost character by character

284
00:11:07,150 --> 00:11:07,870
what I'm typing.

285
00:11:08,370 --> 00:11:09,490
Why did we do that?

286
00:11:09,550 --> 00:11:11,730
It's because with today's instant messaging tools, you

287
00:11:11,730 --> 00:11:14,250
spend half of your time looking at it,

288
00:11:14,290 --> 00:11:16,890
saying, Stephanie is typing, she's typing, she's typing,

289
00:11:17,050 --> 00:11:19,630
she's typing, and then you see what she

290
00:11:19,630 --> 00:11:19,930
said.

291
00:11:21,210 --> 00:11:21,630
Thank you.

292
00:11:23,890 --> 00:11:26,670
But because, in general, you can start formulating

293
00:11:26,670 --> 00:11:29,310
your own reply before Stephanie is done typing

294
00:11:29,310 --> 00:11:29,810
hers.

295
00:11:30,010 --> 00:11:32,490
By doing this live transmission, you end up

296
00:11:32,490 --> 00:11:34,190
spending 100% of your time either reading

297
00:11:34,190 --> 00:11:36,910
or writing, which dramatically speeds up the conversation.

298
00:11:37,250 --> 00:11:38,910
Now, needless to say, there are times you

299
00:11:38,910 --> 00:11:41,250
don't want everyone to see every keystroke, in

300
00:11:41,250 --> 00:11:44,110
particular if you spell like I do, and

301
00:11:44,110 --> 00:11:46,470
so we have this checkbox here.

302
00:11:46,530 --> 00:11:47,610
All you have to do is check it,

303
00:11:47,690 --> 00:11:48,970
and now no one can see what you're

304
00:11:48,970 --> 00:11:50,750
typing until you hit that done button.

305
00:11:50,990 --> 00:11:52,390
This is one of the features we haven't

306
00:11:52,390 --> 00:11:53,710
implemented quite yet.

307
00:11:58,590 --> 00:12:00,830
Okay, and so that's how email conversations, or

308
00:12:00,830 --> 00:12:03,870
rather email-type conversations and instant messaging-type

309
00:12:03,870 --> 00:12:06,650
conversations no longer require two separate tools.

310
00:12:07,370 --> 00:12:08,770
Next thing we want to show you is

311
00:12:08,770 --> 00:12:10,310
how easy it is to add a new

312
00:12:10,310 --> 00:12:12,710
person to an ongoing conversation.

313
00:12:12,950 --> 00:12:14,930
Can I just introduce my brother, Jens, by

314
00:12:14,930 --> 00:12:15,230
the way?

315
00:12:15,330 --> 00:12:16,250
Give him a hand, please.

316
00:12:22,670 --> 00:12:25,050
So we want to add Jens to the

317
00:12:25,050 --> 00:12:25,530
conversation.

318
00:12:25,810 --> 00:12:27,530
If this was email, I would take the

319
00:12:27,530 --> 00:12:29,670
