340
00:13:14,770 --> 00:13:16,190
and by the time I'm added, they could

341
00:13:16,190 --> 00:13:17,410
be arbitrarily far apart.

342
00:13:17,850 --> 00:13:20,050
So we added a feature called Playback.

343
00:13:20,850 --> 00:13:23,150
So I get to see Lars' original message,

344
00:13:23,730 --> 00:13:26,970
Lars asks Stephanie, Stephanie replies, Stephanie does an

345
00:13:26,970 --> 00:13:30,190
inline reply, and so on and so on.

346
00:13:32,670 --> 00:13:33,110
Thank you.

347
00:13:34,570 --> 00:13:36,470
So Playback turns out to be a really

348
00:13:36,470 --> 00:13:39,010
useful feature, particularly when a Wave starts picking

349
00:13:39,010 --> 00:13:40,790
up more structure, and we'll show you more

350
00:13:40,790 --> 00:13:41,270
of that later.

351
00:13:41,990 --> 00:13:43,390
But now that I've caught up on this

352
00:13:43,390 --> 00:13:45,650
Wave, I'm going to just add my reply.

353
00:13:48,400 --> 00:13:49,160
Me too.

354
00:13:50,340 --> 00:13:51,560
Oh, I think I crashed.

355
00:13:52,000 --> 00:13:54,080
Did I mention that it's a developer preview?

